Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.88,0:00:03.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“He does not go back on his promise.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:03.52,0:00:05.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, those words say a lot \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.16,0:00:06.92,Default,,0,0,0,,about a person, don’t they? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.92,0:00:09.19,Default,,0,0,0,,What Bible examples are there of those \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.19,0:00:12.43,Default,,0,0,0,,who please Jehovah by keeping their promise? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.43,0:00:14.76,Default,,0,0,0,,And what is in store for those who do so, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.76,0:00:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,even when it is bad for them? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:18.47,0:00:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we know Jesus, of course, \Nis the foremost example \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:21.00,0:00:24.71,Default,,0,0,0,,of one who kept his promise \Nto do Jehovah’s will. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.71,0:00:26.88,Default,,0,0,0,,But imperfect people too \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:26.88,0:00:30.98,Default,,0,0,0,,have displayed loyalty \Nby keeping their promises. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.98,0:00:34.75,Default,,0,0,0,,For instance, in Joshua chapter 9, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.75,0:00:38.69,Default,,0,0,0,,we read that the Gibeonites \Ntricked the chieftains of Israel \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:38.69,0:00:42.19,Default,,0,0,0,,into concluding \Na covenant of peace with them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.19,0:00:47.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Unwittingly, the Israelites \Npromised not to destroy Gibeon. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.20,0:00:49.73,Default,,0,0,0,,What makes this of special interest \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.73,0:00:54.17,Default,,0,0,0,,is that those disguised men \Nwere part of the Hivite nation, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.17,0:00:57.27,Default,,0,0,0,,which was considered \Nto be a threat to Israel. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.27,0:00:59.64,Default,,0,0,0,,At Joshua 10:2, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.64,0:01:04.00,Default,,0,0,0,,it says \Nthat ‘all of Gibeon’s men were warriors.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.18,0:01:08.35,Default,,0,0,0,,What happened when Israel learned the truth? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.35,0:01:11.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Joshua 9:18 tells us: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.69,0:01:14.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“The Israelites did not attack them, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.19,0:01:16.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“because the chieftains of the assembly \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.96,0:01:19.23,Default,,0,0,0,,“had sworn an oath to them \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:19.23,0:01:22.80,Default,,0,0,0,,by Jehovah the God of Israel.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:22.80,0:01:26.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Did Jehovah approve \Nof their decision not to attack them? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.77,0:01:29.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, he did, as events recorded \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.31,0:01:32.08,Default,,0,0,0,,in Joshua chapter 10 go on to prove. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:32.08,0:01:35.61,Default,,0,0,0,,And we’ll come back to that in a few minutes. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.61,0:01:38.88,Default,,0,0,0,,In another example, \NMordecai urged Esther \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.88,0:01:41.48,Default,,0,0,0,,to go in before King Ahasuerus \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.48,0:01:44.85,Default,,0,0,0,,and plead for his favor \Non behalf of the Jews. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.85,0:01:47.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Esther knew \Nthat going in unannounced \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.19,0:01:49.19,Default,,0,0,0,,could mean her life. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.19,0:01:52.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Mordecai, however, \Nreasoned with her about the matter \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.93,0:01:55.10,Default,,0,0,0,,and the importance of doing so, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.10,0:01:59.30,Default,,0,0,0,,and Esther gave him her word \Nthat she would go in. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.30,0:02:01.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Please notice what she says \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:01.30,0:02:05.81,Default,,0,0,0,,in Esther 4:16, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.81,0:02:07.81,Default,,0,0,0,,in the final part of that verse. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.81,0:02:09.81,Default,,0,0,0,,She’s really giving her word. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.81,0:02:12.35,Default,,0,0,0,,She says: \N“I will go in to the king, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.35,0:02:14.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“which is against the law, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.72,0:02:18.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and if I am to perish, I will perish.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.76,0:02:23.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we know how it turned out \Nfor Esther, Mordecai, and the Jews. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.93,0:02:25.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Esther kept her word, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.93,0:02:28.46,Default,,0,0,0,,and they were all blessed for it, \Nweren’t they? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.46,0:02:31.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Why did such ones live up to their word? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.47,0:02:33.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Because, among other things, \Nthey had qualities, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.87,0:02:38.47,Default,,0,0,0,,such as faith, loyalty, \Nand love for Jehovah and for others. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.47,0:02:43.48,Default,,0,0,0,,The chieftains of Israel had faith \Nand viewed Jehovah as real \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.48,0:02:47.48,Default,,0,0,0,,and were aware \Nof their promise to the Gibeonites. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.48,0:02:52.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Out of faith and loyalty, \Nthey would not go back on their word. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.02,0:02:56.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Also, Esther was moved by love \Nto see the greater good \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.73,0:03:01.06,Default,,0,0,0,,and to put her own life at risk \Nin order to help her people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.06,0:03:03.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, going back to our second question, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.90,0:03:06.70,Default,,0,0,0,,What is in store for those \Nwho keep their promises \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.70,0:03:09.94,Default,,0,0,0,,even when it is bad for them? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.94,0:03:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s look at the principle \Nfound at Mark 4:24. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.41,0:03:19.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, here Jesus said in part: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.12,0:03:23.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“With the measure that you are measuring out, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.89,0:03:26.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“you will have it measured out to you, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.72,0:03:30.89,Default,,0,0,0,,yes, you will have more added to you.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.89,0:03:33.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, what is the principle here? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.60,0:03:35.60,Default,,0,0,0,,As the context shows, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.60,0:03:38.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus was speaking about a person \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.53,0:03:42.27,Default,,0,0,0,,receiving information and enlightenment \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.27,0:03:45.11,Default,,0,0,0,,by paying attention to his words. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.11,0:03:48.58,Default,,0,0,0,,But this thought of having “more added” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.58,0:03:50.58,Default,,0,0,0,,can be seen in many ways. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.58,0:03:54.52,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, \Nwhen we’re loyal to Jehovah, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.52,0:03:58.37,Default,,0,0,0,,he often blesses us \Nwith more than we might expect. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.37,0:04:00.81,Default,,0,0,0,,At times, even a surprise. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.81,0:04:03.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Psalm 84:11 says of him: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.81,0:04:07.08,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jehovah will not hold back anything good \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.08,0:04:10.03,Default,,0,0,0,,from those walking in integrity.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.03,0:04:14.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, going back to what happened \Nwith Israel and the Gibeonites, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.50,0:04:16.87,Default,,0,0,0,,we read in Joshua chapter 8 \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.87,0:04:20.28,Default,,0,0,0,,that in an earlier battle against Ai, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.28,0:04:24.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah helped Israel \Nwith a strategy that led to victory. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.41,0:04:26.42,Default,,0,0,0,,But the account does not say \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.42,0:04:30.89,Default,,0,0,0,,that He performed \Nastounding miracles in doing so. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.89,0:04:34.92,Default,,0,0,0,,On the other hand, in Joshua chapter 10, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.92,0:04:37.66,Default,,0,0,0,,we find something more. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.66,0:04:40.66,Default,,0,0,0,,After the Gibeonites \Ntricked the chieftains of Israel \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.66,0:04:43.55,Default,,0,0,0,,into making that covenant of peace with them, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.55,0:04:48.57,Default,,0,0,0,,the Gibeonites were threatened \Nby an alliance of five kings of the Amorites. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.57,0:04:50.94,Default,,0,0,0,,What would the Israelites do? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.94,0:04:53.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, as we know, they kept their promise \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.41,0:04:56.86,Default,,0,0,0,,and went out to defend the Gibeonites. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.86,0:04:59.18,Default,,0,0,0,,In verse 7 of chapter 10, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.18,0:05:04.04,Default,,0,0,0,,we read that Joshua \Nand all his fighting men went out to do this, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.04,0:05:08.26,Default,,0,0,0,,and as they kept their word, \NJehovah blessed them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.26,0:05:11.34,Default,,0,0,0,,In verse 8, he said to them: \N“Do not be afraid . . . \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.34,0:05:16.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Not one of them \Nwill be able to stand against you.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.28,0:05:19.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, Jehovah was pleased \Nwith their decision, wasn’t he? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.89,0:05:22.92,Default,,0,0,0,,He showed his approval in a marvelous way. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.92,0:05:26.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Giant hailstones \Ndropped down on their enemies, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.66,0:05:30.40,Default,,0,0,0,,and even the sun \Nremained motionless in the sky \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.40,0:05:32.40,Default,,0,0,0,,for about a whole day. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.40,0:05:35.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Chapter 10 and verse 14 says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.74,0:05:38.47,Default,,0,0,0,,“There has never been a day like that one, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.47,0:05:40.74,Default,,0,0,0,,“either before it or after it, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.74,0:05:43.91,Default,,0,0,0,,“when Jehovah listened to the voice of a man, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.91,0:05:47.66,Default,,0,0,0,,for Jehovah was fighting for Israel.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.66,0:05:49.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, Jehovah really loved the Israelites, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.77,0:05:51.78,Default,,0,0,0,,didn’t he\N—for keeping their promise? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.78,0:05:55.69,Default,,0,0,0,,And when the Israelites went to war \Nfor Gibeon, He supported them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.69,0:05:58.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Or as they say, “He poured it on.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.93,0:06:01.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you ever sensed \NJehovah doing that for you \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.88,0:06:05.92,Default,,0,0,0,,when you stick to a difficult task, \Nto a promise? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:05.92,0:06:07.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn’t it true that when we do so, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.92,0:06:12.47,Default,,0,0,0,,we often look back and see blessings \Nthat we never anticipated? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.47,0:06:14.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Among other things, \Nwe might be surprised \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.67,0:06:16.99,Default,,0,0,0,,at how our faith has grown, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.99,0:06:19.33,Default,,0,0,0,,how our love has deepened, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.33,0:06:24.08,Default,,0,0,0,,and how things that we \Nmay have once viewed as overwhelming \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.08,0:06:26.17,Default,,0,0,0,,are now manageable. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.17,0:06:29.04,Default,,0,0,0,,One Bethelite who endured in his assignment \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.04,0:06:32.74,Default,,0,0,0,,in spite of the loss of his mother said this \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.74,0:06:35.38,Default,,0,0,0,,—he also included \Nsome mistreatment by others—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.38,0:06:38.30,Default,,0,0,0,,he said: \N“Sometimes we go through something \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.30,0:06:40.55,Default,,0,0,0,,“we’ve never experienced before, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.55,0:06:42.82,Default,,0,0,0,,“and we may not understand why Jehovah \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.82,0:06:45.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“does not do a specific thing we request. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.69,0:06:48.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“But when we endure, we see, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.89,0:06:53.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“one, his greater comprehension \Nof the overall situation \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.18,0:06:57.05,Default,,0,0,0,,“and, two, his desire for us to rely on him \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.05,0:06:59.39,Default,,0,0,0,,“and know that he’s there for us, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.39,0:07:02.05,Default,,0,0,0,,“and that we’ve not lost his favor \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.05,0:07:05.26,Default,,0,0,0,,“when we experience \Na difficult time in our life. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.26,0:07:07.33,Default,,0,0,0,,“As Jehovah helps us, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.33,0:07:10.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“we have to do as Genesis 24:21 says \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.96,0:07:15.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and ‘stare in amazement’ \Nas he answers our prayers.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.66,0:07:18.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, that’s a beautiful thought. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.67,0:07:20.97,Default,,0,0,0,,And so the blessings may take a while, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.97,0:07:24.18,Default,,0,0,0,,but we can trust that Jehovah \Nwill be there to help us \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.18,0:07:26.21,Default,,0,0,0,,at the right time. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.21,0:07:28.23,Default,,0,0,0,,That happened with Job. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.23,0:07:33.02,Default,,0,0,0,,He once said: “Until I die, \NI will not renounce my integrity!” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.02,0:07:35.94,Default,,0,0,0,,And he lived up to those words, didn’t he? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.94,0:07:39.49,Default,,0,0,0,,So much so that after enduring \Ngreat sorrow and suffering \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.49,0:07:41.56,Default,,0,0,0,,he was able to say: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.56,0:07:43.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“My ears have heard about you, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.86,0:07:47.23,Default,,0,0,0,,but now I do see you with my eyes.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.23,0:07:49.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, Job’s faith grew. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.74,0:07:53.74,Default,,0,0,0,,And, as we know, \NJehovah eventually restored Job’s health, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.74,0:07:58.64,Default,,0,0,0,,doubled his wealth, \Nand blessed him with a beautiful family. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.64,0:08:01.10,Default,,0,0,0,,We benefit from such Bible accounts. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.10,0:08:04.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Like Jehovah’s servants in the past, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.15,0:08:06.65,Default,,0,0,0,,we may suffer from persecution, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.65,0:08:10.01,Default,,0,0,0,,injustice, disasters, grief, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.01,0:08:13.09,Default,,0,0,0,,disappointments, or serious illness. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.09,0:08:16.13,Default,,0,0,0,,In addition, \Nwe may have to work hard \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.13,0:08:20.13,Default,,0,0,0,,to fulfill our promise \Nto be a good husband, wife, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.13,0:08:22.90,Default,,0,0,0,,or a friend in time of need. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.90,0:08:24.69,Default,,0,0,0,,The list is long. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.69,0:08:29.11,Default,,0,0,0,,And despite the difficulties \Nor even the pain at times, we can do it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.11,0:08:33.71,Default,,0,0,0,,We can imitate the faith \Nof past and present examples \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.71,0:08:36.02,Default,,0,0,0,,and live up to our promises\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.02,0:08:41.75,Default,,0,0,0,,—including, of course, \Nour dedication vow to Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.75,0:08:45.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Since Jehovah often does more \Nfor us than we might expect, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.73,0:08:50.16,Default,,0,0,0,,we’re confident \Nthat what he holds out for our future \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.16,0:08:52.90,Default,,0,0,0,,is greater than we can now imagine. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.90,0:08:56.50,Default,,0,0,0,,As Psalm 31:19 says of Jehovah: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.50,0:08:59.09,Default,,0,0,0,,“How abundant your goodness is! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.09,0:09:02.21,Default,,0,0,0,,You have stored it up \Nfor those who fear you.”\N
